<p> <%= link_to 'Management by Objectives', 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Management_by_objectives' %> was first discussed by Peter Drucker in 1954 (yes 50 years ago) and since then objectives or goals have
	been used to steer businesses. In the 1990's we used the <strong>Balanced Scorcard</strong> management framework to cascade goals and now ITIL and COBIT do the same. COBIT
	provides guidance on how to use the balanced scorecard with their framework in the freely available kit.
	</p>

<p>Using the   <%= link_to ' Balanced Scorecard', 'http://www.ap-institute.com/Balanced%20Scorecard.html' %>    approach, you divide your goals in 4 categories
	<hr /><hr />
	<ul>
		<li>Financial</li>
		<li>Customer</li>
		<li>Internal Process</li>
		<li>Learning and Growth</li>
	</ul>
	
	Working from the enterprise drivers to produce Enterprise Goals and then cascading these goals to the lines of business and down to the teams, you end up with real measurable actions
	that will align the workers to the enterprise direction.
	</p>
	</div>
</div>
