			progress towards yours and the teams goals regularly. Regual employee engagement is extremely important in this process.</p>	

<div>
<p>Goals need to be SMART.</p>

<h1 class = " pull-left">S<small>pecific</small> </h1><hr />
<h1 class = " pull-left">M<small>easureable</small></h1><hr />
<h1 class = " pull-left">A<small>ttainable</small></h1><hr />
<h1 class = " pull-left">R<small>ealistic</small></h1><hr />
<h1 class = " pull-left">T<small>imely</small></h1>




<p class = " pull-left">You will find a great deal of guidance on the web on how to make sure you set smart goals and how to cascade these goals to the team. As a manager,
	this is your opportunity to get your employee's on board with the companies program. Do not rush through this step and do not focus on just the easily measureable goals.
	This is your best chance to achieve the cultural changes that maybe required to improve service levels. You will not find these types of softer goals in the generic sets on the web.</p>
	<p class = " pull-left">An example is where you may decide to ask the team to each share in the production of the monthly department magazine/blog. You are aiming to improve morale. You
		normally do not find "improve morale" on the business goals but you always find "improve costs"	and it is well know that a happy team are more efficient and effective.
		</p>
		<p class = " pull-left">I have seen companies that put their employees well being on the radar as part of their goals.</p>
			

